04808nam a22006975i 9781501703874DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20162016nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979836787  a97815017038747 a10.7591/97815017038742doi  a(DE-B1597)480088  a(OCoLC)949885894  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aMED0490002bisacsh1 aLazris, Andy, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCuring Medicare :bA Doctor's View on How Our Health Care System Is Failing Older Americans and How We Can Fix It /cAndy Lazris. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (264 p.) :b2 line figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Culture and Politics of Health Care Work00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: My Boss -- t1. Defining Quality: The Quest for Numerical Perfection -- t2. Defining Thorough: Finding and Fixing Everything -- t3. Excessive Specialization, Expectation, and Litigation -- t4. Hospitalization: The Pinnacle of Thorough -- t5. Long-Term Care: The Unwitting Geriatric ICU -- t6. Quality and Value: Moving toward a Cure -- tAfterword: Redefining Thorough -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAndy Lazris, MD, is a practicing primary care physician who experiences the effects of Medicare policy on a daily basis. As a result, he believes that the way we care for our elderly has taken a wrong turn and that Medicare is complicit in creating the very problems it seeks to solve. Aging is not a disease to be cured; it is a life stage to be lived. Lazris argues that aggressive treatments cannot change that fact but only get in the way and decrease quality of life. Unfortunately, Medicare's payment structure and rules deprive the elderly of the chance to pursue less aggressive care, which often yields the most humane and effective results. Medicare encourages and will pay more readily for hospitalization than for palliative and home care. It encourages and pays for high-tech assaults on disease rather than for the primary care that can make a real difference in the lives of the elderly.Lazris offers straightforward solutions to ensure Medicare’s solvency through sensible cost-effective plans that do not restrict patient choice or negate the doctor-patient relationship. Using both data and personal stories, he shows how Medicare needs to change in structure and purpose as the population ages, the physician pool becomes more specialized, and new medical technology becomes available. Curing Medicare demonstrates which medical interventions (medicines, tests, procedures) work and which can be harmful in many common conditions in the elderly; the harms and benefits of hospitalization; the current culture of long-term care; and how Medicare often promotes care that is ineffective, expensive, and contrary to what many elderly patients and their families really want.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 4aAging. 4aConsumer Health & Fitness. 4aSociology & Social Science. 7aMEDICAL / Medicaid & Medicare.2bisacsh1 aBrownlee, Shannon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrownlee, Shannon.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066749340uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501703874zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501703874423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501703874/original  a978-3-11-066749-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MDPM  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MDPM  aEBA_EEBK